          <div id="id5" style="height: 100px; left: 10px; position: absolute; top: 1544px; width: 766px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_4 shape-with-text">
            <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_766_100" style="padding: 0px; ">
              <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="Summary_Body">This term is the illusive term which answers almost all our questions. If we have constant rates then derivative of p with r becomes 0 and hence forward and future prices are same! (As per common logic). <br /></p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          


          <div id="id6" style="height: 561px; left: 738px; position: absolute; top: 17px; width: 247px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_4 shape-with-text">
            <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_247_561" style="padding: 0px; ">
              <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">Simple Notations<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">V(S,r,t) = Price of a Forward contract when interest rates (r) are stochastic. <br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">assuming dS = r S dt + sigma S dX<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">dr = u r dt + w r dX1<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">and E[dX dX1] = rho (correlation term)...usual symbols.<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">Triangle = Delta<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">S = Spot<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">r = interest rate<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">Z = $1 Zero coupon Bond<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">I haven’t included cross gamma term in the first application of Ito lemma (cross due to S,r correlation). It just makes the equation more ugly than it already is....<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">Hedging means canceling the dX terms so delta’s (triangle terms) are chosen. You can solve it on paper and verify. <br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">Logic in last line is simply<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">if f(x) = f(y)<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">or x^2 + x = y^2 + y<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">then of course both LHS and RHS are independent of x and y otherwise they can’t be equal.<br /></p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          


          <div id="id7" style="height: 389px; left: 643px; position: absolute; top: 1093px; width: 261px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_4 shape-with-text">
            <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_261_389" style="padding: 0px; ">
              <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="Summary_Body">Here the assumption is that future contract has value 0 at time t = 0. Using similarity solution, F = S/Z (from previous picture), here I assume that future = S / p.<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body">I find the equation of p and compare it with Z to find the cause of price difference.<br /></p>
                <p class="Summary_Body"><br /></p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          


